    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In carpentry, mortise-and-tenon joints where the projecting tongue (tenon) of one piece is round in cross-section, made to fit into the corresponding round cutout (mortise) in the other piece.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000019701/Hoadley, Understanding Wood (1980)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000029801/Jobe and Kaye, New England Furniture (1984)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Im Zimmermannshandwerk eine Zapfenverbindung, bei der die vorstehende Zunge (Zapfen) des einen Stückes im Querschnitt rund ist, um in den entsprechenden runden Ausschnitt (Nut) des anderen Stückes zu passen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
